{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":4566,"record_hash":"sha256:dfa504f9a0106741f19c0ee99e3410ad437f7e68813eda9d5c254ce07963dda3","timestamp":"2026-05-07T15:50:05.503Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"::code-comment{title=\"[P2] Sensitive keys do not force redaction\" body=\"The object walk redacts string values only by value shape, without considering the field name. Low-entropy values under keys like `token`, `api_key`, `secret`, `password`, or `authorization` can survive and still be reported as unredacted. A tiny key denylist for string values feels POC-sized and high value.\" file=\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs\" start=38 end=46 priority=2 confidence=0.82}\n\n::code-comment{title=\"[P2] Prefixed UUIDs can still be redacted\" body=\"UUIDs are preserved only when the whole candidate is exactly a UUID. Since `_`, `/`, and `=` are candidate bytes, common strings like `[REDACTED:entropy]` or `[REDACTED:entropy]` can be scanned as one high-entropy candidate and redacted even though UUIDs are intended to survive.\" file=\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs\" start=99 end=112 priority=2 confidence=0.87}\n\n::code-comment{title=\"[P3] JSON keys bypass redaction\" body=\"Object keys are copied unchanged, so a transcript record that puts a token-like string in a JSON member name will store it verbatim. That is probably less common than value leakage, but if the redactor claims to protect stored `source_record`, this should either be explicitly scoped as value-only or handled with collision-safe key placeholders.\" file=\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs\" start=40 end=46 priority=3 confidence=0.78}\n\n::code-comment{title=\"[P3] Git SHAs are now likely redacted\" body=\"The long-hex rule catches 32+ character high-entropy hex strings, which includes normal Git object IDs in transcript/tool output. This is a defensible privacy tradeoff for the POC, but it will erase useful provenance unless we add contextual exemptions later.\" file=\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs\" start=115 end=119 priority=3 confidence=0.88}\n\nNo P1s came back this time. The slashy-base64 leak looks fixed, and the docs are not overselling this as publish-grade secret scanning. Local checks also passed: `cargo test -p but-agentlog redaction --lib` and `cargo clippy -p but-agentlog --all-targets --no-deps`.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-07T15:50:05.503Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}